Import and Process Data

Tribes data comes from an .RData file that Justin created (documentation available in ’data wrangle change score centroid and map data.R`). Precipitation and EPA data are stored in R_Analysis > _Variables.

# Set working directory
setwd("/Users/kathrynmcconnell/Documents/GitHub/tribal_lands2/R_Analysis/_Variables")

# Download tribes data and select distinct records only
load("/Users/kathrynmcconnell/Documents/GitHub/tribal_lands2/R_Analysis/processed_data.RData")
data_long <- distinct(merged_data_record_all_long, tribe, time, FIPS, .keep_all = TRUE)

# Import EPA climate change and precipitation variables to be joined to tribes data
climate <- read_csv("EPA_CSRI_Index_Final.csv") %>% select(FIPS, FIPS_manual, Risk, CRSI)
precip <- read_csv("MeanAnnualPrecipitation.csv") %>% select(FIPS, MeanAnnualPrecipitation_in)

Process data.

# In EPA climate data, for counties that are missing automatic FIPS designations use manual FIPS designation instead
climate[1:126,]$FIPS <- climate[1:126,]$FIPS_manual

# For all three datasets, change FIPS from character to integer to make future joins function
climate$FIPS <- as.numeric(climate$FIPS) 
precip$FIPS <- as.numeric(precip$FIPS)
data_long$FIPS <- as.numeric(data_long$FIPS)

Join precipitation and EPA climate data to tribes dataframe.

# Join new variables to all tribe records 
main_join1 <- left_join(data_long, precip, c("FIPS" = "FIPS")) %>% 
  left_join(climate, c("FIPS" = "FIPS")) %>% 
  mutate(Precip = MeanAnnualPrecipitation_in) %>% 
  select(-(FIPS_manual)) %>% 
  select(-(MeanAnnualPrecipitation_in))

Create data.frame to include only tribes with time 1 and 2 data.

data_t1and2_long <- filter(main_join1, tribe %in% tribes_time1and2_lst$tribe)

# Change FIPS from character to numeric
data_t1and2_long$FIPS <- as.numeric(data_t1and2_long$FIPS)

Check Data First, confirm the data is correct, each tribe should have 2 summarized records in total, one for time 1 and one for time 2, so the resulted data.frame should has 0 row.

t1and2_lst <- group_by(data_t1and2_long, tribe, time) %>% 
  count() %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(tribe) %>%
  count() %>%
  filter(nn < 2)

nrow(t1and2_lst)
## [1] 0

Exploratory Analyses

Plot Precipitation and EPA Risk Variable

All Tribes, including those with time 1 or time 2 data only

  • Because the total number of counties with tribes present was reduced so much between t1 and t2, it’s difficult to get a sense of exactly how the precipitation distributions differ. However it does seem that the t2 distribution may skew more towards lower precipitation.
  • EPA’s risk score seems to be more evenly distributed across counties with tribes present at t2 than at t1 (where it is skewed toward lower risk). Of note, in the box plot there is a cluster of counties at t2 around risk = .65 that are likely also geographically clustered, and would be interesting to look into.

Precipitation for all tribes

ggplot(main_join1, aes(Precip, fill = time)) +
  geom_histogram(position = "dodge", binwidth = 200) +
  theme_minimal() +
  ylab("Count of Counties with Tribes Present") +
  xlab("Mean Annual Precipitation (in)") +
  facet_wrap(~ time, nrow = 2)

ggplot(main_join1, aes(time, Precip, colour = time)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_quasirandom(alpha = 1/10, varwidth = TRUE) +
  theme_minimal() +
  ylab("Mean Annual Precipitation (in)") +
  ggtitle("Counties with Tribes Present at Time 1 & 2", "All Tribes")

Test for Significant Difference

Examine whether Precipitation and EPA Risk distributions seem to be approximately normal

  • None of these variables seem to be normally distributed (though Precipitation distributions come closer than EPA Risk). However, for all distributions the issue seems to be at the tails, so a transformation might help us move forward.

Make Q-Q plots for Precipitation and EPA Risk for all counties with tribes and counties with tribes that have data at both t1 and t2. Q-Q plots show the actual data (y axis) plotted against the theoretical data of a normal distribution (x axis). If the actual data are normally distributed, the points should roughly fall along a 45 degree line.

# Download library used for Q-Q plot. 
library(ggpubr)

# Graph Q-Q plots
ggqqplot(main_join1$Risk) + ggtitle("EPA Risk, All Tribes")

ggqqplot(data_t1and2_long$Risk) + ggtitle("EPA Risk, Only Tribes with T1 and T2")

ggqqplot(main_join1$Precip) + ggtitle("Precipitation, All Tribes")

ggqqplot(data_t1and2_long$Precip) + ggtitle("Precipitation, Only Tribes with T1 and T2")

Run preliminary t-tests

  • Here I do not use a Wilcoxon rank sum test because the variables are continuously distributed. Instead I start with simple t-tests.
  • There is not a statistically significant difference between Precipitation at t1 and at t2 for either all tribes or for tribes at only t1 and t2.
  • The difference in EPA Risk at t1 and t2 is statistically significant at p = .05 for all tribes but not for tribes only at t1 and t2.
# T-test for all tribe-counties and precipitation
precip_all_ttest <- t.test(main_join1$Precip[main_join1$time == "time 1"], 
                           main_join1$Precip[main_join1$time == "time 2"])

precip_all_ttest
